I2C Protocol in IoT Sensor Communication
I2C (Inter-Integrated Circuit) is a synchronous serial communication protocol used to connect a microcontroller (such as Arduino, ESP32, or Raspberry Pi) with multiple sensors and peripheral devices using only two communication wires. It is widely used in IoT because it reduces wiring complexity and allows multiple devices to share the same communication bus.

SDA and SCL Lines
I2C uses two signal lines:

SDA (Serial Data Line):
Transfers data between the master and slave devices.
It is a bidirectional line, meaning it can both send and receive data.

SCL (Serial Clock Line):
Carries the clock signal generated by the master device.
Synchronizes the data transfer on the SDA line.

Thus, only two wires (SDA and SCL) are required for communication, regardless of how many I2C devices are connected.


How I2C Addressing Works
I2C follows a master-slave architecture.

The master (e.g., Arduino or ESP32) starts communication.
It sends the address of the desired slave device.
Every sensor on the bus checks the address.
Only the sensor whose address matches responds; all others ignore the message.
The master then reads data from or writes data to that sensor.


Three Common IoT Sensors that Use I2C
BMP280 – Measures atmospheric pressure and temperature.
BME280 – Measures temperature, humidity, and pressure.
MPU6050 – Measures acceleration and angular velocity.
